This tasty cocktail recipe has been created by Erik Lorincz from Kwānt, No.47 in The World’s 50 Best Bars 2019, with Monkey Shoulder whisky. Will you be giving it a try?

25ml Monkey Shoulder
25ml Calvados
10ml Mezcal
10ml oloroso sherry
50ml oat milk
5g zatar
15g demerara sugar 
Garnished with floregano •

𝑻𝒉𝒂𝒏𝒌𝒔 𝒕𝒐 🍸 @cocktailpete 

Yeah yeah it sounds dramatic 😂 but no harming grenades today 😉 instead a pleasing sour, where I pairred whisky and brandy for the base 👍 green apple syrup and grenadine for the sweet part 🍏 lemon juice for the sour counter part 🍋 and fluffy egg white on top 🥚 enjoy 

The 🍹 English grenade 

45 ml whisky english
15 ml apple brandy
25 ml fresh organic lemon juice
10 ml green apple syrup
10 ml grenadine
egg white 

Pour all ingredients in a shaker and give it a hard shake 🕺 add ice 🧊 shake untill chilled ❄ double strain into a chilled glass ❄ garnish with dehydrated lemon 🍋 and freezedried apple 

Cheers 🥂 Skål

Through these burrows, she began to experience arousal, desire, and one day, love. She fell in love with a brave and handsome warrior named Chag. He did not feel worthy of the goddess. In her desperation, she offered him to drink the luxurious elixir that poured from her heart. He drank and drank until he drunkenly declared, “make me a god or become a woman” ... and that’s where the legend ends. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

Neanderthal is a member of a group of archaic humans who emerged at least 200,000 years ago. Neanderthals were replaced or assimilated by early modern human populations (Homo sapiens) between 35,000 and perhaps 24,000 years ago. The name Neanderthal derives from the Neander Valley (German Neander Thal or Neander Tal) in Germany, where the fossils were first found. Recently, it was reported that Eurasians generally carry about 2 percent Neanderthal nuclear DNA, which suggests that modern humans and Neanderthals interbred and thus were not two different biological species, despite most classifications treating them as such!

𝑻𝒉𝒂𝒏𝒌𝒔 𝒕𝒐 🍸 @cheerstohappyhour 

(Recipe Included) 

There’s nothing like a drink so tasty it literally has two countries arguing to declare ownership over it. Pisco, is a grape-based spirit similar to brandy, known as both the Peruvian and Chilean National drink. One notable similarity between the two Pisco providers is the grapes used to make it are typically grown in very dry areas of the two countries, causing the vines to produce a lower volume of grapes but create a higher concentration of flavour and aromas.
.
Fun Fact: Pisco can only legally be distilled once and distillers are not allowed to use water to regulate the spirits ABV, so they must distil the it to proof.
.
If you wanna get down to the best part of Pisco (the drinking part) here’s a tasty little number I had while visiting the crew at @suite114.to.
.
Drink: Southern Hemisphere
Recipe by: @Saint.yarai
1oz Pisco
1oz Lemon Juice
1oz Strawberry Puree
0.25 Giffard vanilla
0.25oz simple syrup
0.75oz egg white
Strained over 1oz Prosecco
.
(Method)
Shake all ingredients less the Prosecco. Add Prosecco to a coupe glass and pour mixture on top of it. Let egg white foam settle and then spritz Ms Better Bitters Sumac and kiwi bitters on top using an atomizer and stencil.
